illies-l'Abbaye, Hainaut, Belgique":"Bersillies-l'Abbaye, Henegouwen, België"},"en":{"1340–ABT 11 OCT 1388":"1340–about 11 October 1388","1340–1388":"1340–1388","1316–1378":"1316–1378","1365–1434":"1365–1434","1310–Male":"1310–Deceased","1312–Female":"1312–Deceased","1316":"1316","1434":"1434","1312":"1312","1378":"1378","1388":"1388","1365":"1365","1310":"1310","1364":"1364","1340":"1340","before 1340":"before 1340","4 septembre 1378":"4 September 1378","ABT 11 OCT 1388":"about 11 October 1388","(La Thure)":"La Thurelle, Seine-et-Marne, Île-de-France, France","Europe":"Europe","Bersillies-l'Abbaye, Hainaut, Belgique":"Bersillies-l'Abbaye, Hainaut, Belgium","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gavre","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alphonse, Cecile, Chantal, Francoise, Jacques, Julien, Laurent.","French: occupational name for a blacksmith or ironworker, from a regional form of Old French <i>fevre</i> (see   Lefevre  ). Compare   Farve   and   Faver  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Faver","meanings":["Altered form of French   Favre   ‘blacksmith’ or of its cognate <b>Lefèvre</b> (see   Lefevre  ). Compare   Favor  .","English: probably in most cases an altered form of   Feaver  , partly because between the 16th and the 18th centuries its pronunciation was sometimes identical with the word favour (see 4 below).","English: occasionally perhaps also a nickname from Middle English (Old French) <i>favo(u)r</i>, Middle English <i>faver</i> ‘help, beauty, grace, benevolence’."]},{"name":"Lefevre","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Andre, Emile, Jacques, Joffre, Luc, Adrien, Antoine, Armand, Camille, Eunide, Francois, Germaine.","French and Walloon (<b>Lefèvre</b>): occupational name for a blacksmith or ironworker, Old French <i>fevre</i>, with fused masculine definite article <i>le</i>. One of the most common surnames in France from an early date, coined before the French word for smith, <i>fèvre</i> (from Latin <i>faber</i> ‘maker’), was replaced by <i>forgeron</i>. This surname was also brought to England (in the 16th century by Protestant Walloons and later reinforced by Huguenots from France). It is also established in the Flemish part of Belgium and in Haiti. See also   Lefebvre  , compare   Faver  ,   Lafaver  ,   Lafever  ,   Lefever  , and   Leffew  .","History: This surname is listed (in the form <i>Le Fèvre</i>) in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of America (in the form <i>Le Fevre</i>)."]},{"name":"Favret","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Jacques, Andre, Chantel, Raoul.","French: diminutive of   Favre   ‘blacksmith’."]},{"name":"Farve","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Cecile.","Altered form of French   Favre   ‘blacksmith’."]}]},{"name":"Yolande","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of uncertain origin ."],"variants":[{"name":"Yolanda","meanings":["Of uncertain origin. It is found in Old French as  <b>Yolande</b> , of which this is a Latinate form. It may be ultimately of Germanic origin, but if so it has been altered beyond recognition. It is also sometimes identified with the name of St <i>Jolenta</i> (  d. 1298 ), daughter of the king of Hungary."]}]},{"name":"dite","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  See  Dyte  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dyte","meanings":["English: nickname, perhaps from an unrecorded Middle English * <i>dight</i>, a side-form of Middle English  <i>dought</i> ‘brave, valiant’, and possibly derived therefore from a shortened form of Old English  <i>dyhtig</i>,  <i>dohtig</i> ‘doughty’.  Compare  Doughty  ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Lens","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Helene   or   Magdalene  , also used as an independent given name."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Yolande dite de Lens Gavre was born in 1340, her father, Gérard DE GAVRE, was 31 and her mother, Marie DE SHOENWOUSTRE, was 29. She married Jean III de Barbençon in 1364, in Europe. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died about 11 October 1388, in La Thurelle, Seine-et-Marne, Île-de-France, France, at the age of 48."},"et":{"1340–ABT 11 OCT 1388":"1340–umbes 11. oktoober 1388","1340–1388":"1340–1388","1316–1378":"1316–1378","1365–1434":"1365–1434","1310–Male":"1310–Surnud","1312–Female":"1312–Surnud","1316":"1316","1434":"1434","1312":"1312","1378":"1378","1388":"1388","1365":"1365","1310":"1310","1364":"1364","1340":"1340","before 1340":"enne 1340","4 septembre 1378":"4. september 1378","ABT 11 OCT 1388":"umbes 11. oktoober 1388","(La Thure)":"La Thurelle, Seine-et-Marne, Île-de-France, Prantsusmaa","Europe":"Europe","Bersillies-l'Abbaye, Hainaut, Belgique":"Bersillies-l'Abbaye, Hainaut, Belgia"},"fi":{"1340–ABT 11 OCT 1388":"1340–noin 11. lokakuuta 1388","1340–1388":"1340–1388","1316–1378":"1316–1378","1365–1434":"1365–1434","1310–Male":"1310–Kuollut","1312–Female":"1312–Kuollut","1316":"1316","1434":"1434","1312":"1312","1378":"1378","1388":"1388","1365":"1365","1310":"1310","1364":"1364","1340":"1340","before 1340":"ennen vuotta 1340","4 septembre 1378":"4. syyskuuta 1378","ABT 11 OCT 1388":"noin 11. lokakuuta 1388","(La Thure)":"La Thurelle, Seine-et-Marne, Île-de-France, Ranska","Europe":"Europe","Bersillies-l'Abbaye, Hainaut, Belgique":"Bersillies-l'Abbaye, Hainaut, Belgia"},"fr":{"1340–ABT 11 OCT 1388":"1340–environ 11 octobre 1388","1340–1388":"1340–1388","1316–1378":"1316–13